{
  "texts": [
    "In the early development stage of graph neural networks, pooling operation draws on topology-based approaches, and its core idea is to use eigendecomposition to realize the coarsening operation of graphs.",
    "As a typical graph clustering algorithm during this period, Graclus (Dhillon et al. 2007) divides the original complex graph structure into multiple local subgraphs, performs clustering tasks independently for each subgraph, and subsequently integrates the clustering results of each subgraph to construct a global clustering output.",
    "Although this method is still applied as a pooling layer in some recent graph neural network works (Levie et al. 2018; Defferrard et al. 2016), it is worth noting that traditional methods based on matrix eigendecomposition are often accompanied by higher time complexity (Lee et al. 2019; Wu et al. 2020), which limits their real-time processing capabilities on large-scale graph data.",
    "Therefore, to overcome the efficiency limitations of early pooling methods, it is necessary to find new pooling alternatives to better adapt to the processing needs of graph data.",
    "Unlike earlier pooling methods based on eigendecomposition, global pooling uses summation, averaging, maximization, or neural networks to complete the pooling operation in one step."
  ]
}